<chapter xml:id="chapter-paths" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Paths and connectedness</title>

<section xml:id="section-paths-motivation">
<title>Motivation</title>

<example xml:id="example-paths-motivating">
	<title>Driving routes on a graph</title>
	<p>
	Looking at a map of Alberta, you might decide that there are three reasonable driving routes from Camrose to Red Deer and three reasonable driving routes from Red Deer to Drumheller.
	Define a graph <m>G = (V,E)</m> with cities as vertices and routes as edges.
	If we travel between Camrose, Red Deer, and Drumheller on these routes,
	we find that any multi-city trip is a finite sequence from <m>V \cup E</m> which starts and ends at a vertex and alternates between vertices and edges.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-paths-driving-routes">
		<caption>Driving routes between Camrose, Red Deer, and Drumheller.</caption>
		<image width="35%">
			<description>Graph depicting driving routes between Camrose, Red Deer, and Drumheller.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/driving.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	For example,
	<me> C, r_1, R, r_4, D, r_5, R, r_2, C, r_3, R, r_6, D </me>
	is a trip that travels back and forth between Camrose and Drumheller, via Red Deer each time,
	and that never uses the same route twice.
	Notice that we cannot extend this trip without repeating a route.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-paths-walks-trails-paths">
<title>Walks, trails, and paths</title>

<p> Suppose <m>G = (V,E)</m> is a graph. </p>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>walk</title>
		<idx>walk (in a graph)</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>walk</h></idx>
		<p>
		a finite sequence <m>v_0, e_1, v_1, e_2, \dotsc, v_{n - 1}, e_n, v_n</m>
		of elements from <m>V \cup E</m>, with each <m>v_i \in V</m> and each <m>e_i \in E</m>,
		such that edge <m>e_i</m> connects vertices <m>v_{i-1}</m> and <m>v_i</m>
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>closed walk</title>
		<idx><h>walk (in a graph)</h><h>closed</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>walk</h><h>closed</h></idx>
		<p> a walk that ends at the same vertex at which it started (that is, <m>v_n = v_0</m>) </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>open walk</title>
		<idx><h>walk (in a graph)</h><h>open</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>walk</h><h>open</h></idx>
		<p> a walk that isn't closed (that is, <m>v_n \neq v_0</m>) </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>trail</title>
		<idx>trail (in a graph)</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>trail</h></idx>
		<p> a walk that traverses no edge more than once </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>path</title>
		<idx>path (in a graph)</idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>path</h></idx>
		<p> a walk that passes through no vertex more than once, <em>except</em> possibly the endpoints <m>v_0,v_n</m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<note><p> We may also apply the adjectives <term>open</term> and <term>closed</term> to trails and paths. </p></note>

<example><p>
	Consider the graph in <xref ref="example-paths-motivating" />.
	<ol>
		<li> The <q>trip</q> we found in the example is a trail of maximal length starting at vertex <m>C</m>. </li>
		<li>
			The walks <m>C,r_1,R,r_4,D</m> and <m>C,r_1,R,r_2,C</m> are both paths,
			the first open and the second closed.
		</li>
		<li> The walk <m>C,r_1,R,r_4,D,r_4,R</m> is neither a path nor a trail. </li>
	</ol>
</p></example>

<example xml:id="example-paths-and-trails">
	<title>Paths and trails</title>
	<p> Consider the following graph. </p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-paths-illustrative-example">
		<caption>A example graph to illustrate paths and trails.</caption>
		<image width="33%">
			<description>A graph to illustrate paths and trails</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/paths-and-trails.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	This graph has the following properties.
	<ol>
		<li><p>
			Every path or trail passing through <m>v_1</m> must start or end there but cannot be closed,
			<em>except</em> for the closed paths:
			<ul>
				<li> <m>v_1</m>; </li>
				<li> <m>v_1, e_1, v_2, e_1, v_1</m>; </li>
				<li> <m>v_2, e_1, v_1, e_1, v_2</m>; </li>
			</ul>
		</p></li>
		<li> Walk <m>v_1, e_1, v_2, e_5, v_3, e_4, v_4,</m> is both a trail and a path. </li>
		<li> Walk <m>v_1, e_1, v_2, e_5, v_3, e_6, v_3, e_4, v_4,</m> is a trail but not a path. </li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</example>

<problem xml:id="wexample-path-num-trails"> <!-- worked example -->
<!-- \label{WEXAMPLE::num.trails} -->

	<statement><p>
		Consider again the graph in <xref ref="figure-paths-illustrative-example" />
		from <xref ref="example-paths-and-trails" />.
		How many trails from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m> exist?
		How many of those trails are paths?
		Are there any paths from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m> that are <em>not</em> trails?
	</p></statement>

	<solution>
		<p>
		We can solve this using a graph!
		The graph in <xref ref="figure-paths-mapping-trails" /> was created by mapping out all possible trails starting at <m>v_3</m> and ending at <m>v_4</m>, moving across one edge at a time.
		Each node in this new (directed) graph is labelled with a partial walk that is a continuation of the walk assigned to the node above it.
		Each leg in the graph stops when the associated walk being followed reaches <m>v_4</m> and cannot be continued without repeating another edge.
		To save space in the node labels, we have used <q><ellipsis /></q> to mean the walk from the previous node.
		</p>
		<figure xml:id="figure-paths-mapping-trails">
			<caption>Mapping the trails from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m> in the graph of <xref ref="figure-paths-illustrative-example" />.</caption>
			<image>
				<description>A graph to map the possible trails in another graph.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/mapping-trails.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<p>
		Counting all the nodes in the graph of <xref ref="figure-paths-mapping-trails" /> that are labelled with a walk that ends in <m>v_4</m>,
		we see that there are ten trails from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m>.
		Also, we can easily see that only three of the trails are paths.
		</p><p>
		We can use the same technique to map out all paths from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m>,
		but this time we terminate a leg when we cannot move off a vertex without repeating a vertex that is already visited in that walk.
		(Note that the walk <m>v_3,e_6,v_3</m> is a path, but if we extend this walk in any way it will no longer be a path.)
		</p>
		<figure xml:id="figure-paths-mapping-paths">
			<caption>Mapping the paths from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m> in the graph of <xref ref="figure-paths-illustrative-example" />.</caption>
			<image>
				<description>A graph to map the possible paths in another graph.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/mapping-paths.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<p> So there are only three paths from <m>v_3</m> to <m>v_4</m>, and each of them is a trail. </p>
	</solution>

</problem>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-paths-open-is-trail">
	<statement><p> Every open path is a trail. </p></statement>
	<proof>
		<p>
		We will prove the contrapositive: a walk that is not a trail cannot be an open path.
		So suppose <m>W</m> is a walk in a graph, and that <m>W</m> traverses edge <m>e</m> twice.
		</p>
		<case><title>Case <m>e</m> is a loop</title><p> Then <m>W</m> passes through the vertex incident to <m>e</m> at least three times, hence is not a path. </p></case>
		<case><title>Case <m>e</m> is not a loop</title><p>
			Write <m>e=\{v,v'\}</m>.
			Initially, there are two possibilities to consider.
			If each of the two assumed traversals of <m>e</m> moves from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m>, then <m>W</m> passes through each of <m>v,v'</m> at least twice, and hence is not a path.
			If the two assumed traversals of <m>e</m> move <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> and <m>v'</m> to <m>v</m> respectively, then <m>W</m> passes through <m>v</m> at least twice.
			If <m>W</m> traverses <m>v</m> twice because it both starts and ends there, then <m>W</m> is not open.
			If <m>W</m> is open and traverses <m>v</m> twice, then <m>W</m> is not a path.
			So in any case, <m>W</m> is not an open path.
		</p></case>
	</proof>
</proposition>

<note><p>
	In <xref ref="activity-paths-path-trail-counterexmps" />,
	you are asked to create counterexamples of some statements related to the above proposition.
</p></note>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-paths-connected">
<title>Connected vertices, graphs, and components</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-paths-connected-vertices">
		<title>connected vertices</title>
		<idx><h>connected</h><h>vertices (in a graph)</h></idx>
		<idx><h>vertex</h><h>connected</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>connected</h><h>vertices</h></idx>
		<p> a pair of vertices <m>v,v'</m> such that there exists a walk beginning at <m>v</m> and ending at <m>v'</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li xml:id="definition-paths-connected-graph">
		<title>connected graph</title>
		<idx><h>connected</h><h>graph</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>connected</h></idx>
		<idx><h>nonconnected graph</h><see>connected graph</see></idx>
		<p> every pair of vertices is connected </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example><title>A connected graph</title><image width="25%">
	<description>A diagram of an example connected graph.</description>
	<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/connected.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
</image></example>

<example><title>A nonconnected graph</title><image width="30%">
	<description>A diagram of an example nonconnected graph.</description>
	<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/nonconnected.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
</image></example>

<p> Being connected is a symmetric relationship between vertices, and walks connecting vertices can be shortened to paths. </p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-paths-connected-vertices">
	<title>Characterizations of connected vertices</title>
	<statement><p>
		Assume <m>v,v'</m> are vertices in a graph.
		Then the following are equivalent.
		<ol>
			<li xml:id="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-connected"> Vertices <m>v,v'</m> are connected. </li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-walk-forward"> There exists a walk beginning at <m>v</m> and ending at <m>v'</m>. </li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-path-forward"> There exists a path beginning at <m>v</m> and ending at <m>v'</m>. </li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-walk-backward"> There exists a walk beginning at <m>v'</m> and ending at <m>v</m>. </li>
			<li xml:id="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-path-backward"> There exists a path beginning at <m>v'</m> and ending at <m>v</m>. </li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title>
		<p> As usual, we prove the equivalence of multiple statements using a cycle of logical implications. </p>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-connected" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-walk-forward" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p> This is the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-paths-connected-vertices" text="title" /></term>. </p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-walk-forward" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-path-forward" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Suppose <m>v_0, e_1, v_1, \dotsc, v_{n - 1}, e_n, v_n</m> is a walk with <m>v_0 = v</m> and <m>v_n = v'</m>.
			If this walk is not a path, then there is a repeated vertex.
			Suppose <m>v_j = v_i</m> with <m>j \gt i</m>.
			Then
			<me> v_0, e_1, v_1, \dotsc, v_{i-1}, e_i, v_j, e_{j+1}, \dotsc, v_{n - 1}, e_n, v_n </me>
			is also a walk from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m>.
			Keep removing repeated vertices in this way until a path is obtained.
			</p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-path-forward" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-walk-backward" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p> Just reverse the order of the vertices and edges in the path from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m> to obtain a walk in the other direction. </p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-walk-backward" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-path-backward" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p> As before, if the walk from <m>v'</m> to <m>v</m> is not a path, each pair of repeated vertices can be eliminated by <q>snipping out</q> the portion of the walk between them. </p>
		</case>
		<case>
			<title>
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-path-backward" text="local">Statement</xref>
				implies
				<xref ref="proposition-paths-connected-vertices-connected" text="local">Statement</xref>
			</title>
			<p>
			Reverse the path from <m>v'</m> to <m>v</m> to obtain a walk from <m>v</m> to <m>v'</m>,
			thereby satisfying the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-paths-connected-vertices" text="title" /></term>.
			</p>
		</case>
	</proof>
</proposition>

<p>
A nonconnected graph can be considered to simply be a collection of connected subgraphs.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-paths-connected-component-working">
		<title>connected component (working definition)</title>
		<idx><h>connected</h><h>component of a graph, working definition</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>connected</h><h>component (working definition)</h></idx>
		<p> a connected subgraph of a graph which is not contained in any larger connected subgraph of that graph </p>
	</li>
	<li xml:id="definition-paths-connected-component-formal">
		<title>connected component (formal definition)</title>
		<idx><h>connected</h><h>component of a graph, formal definition</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>connected</h><h>component (formal definition)</h></idx>
		<p>
		a subgraph <m>G'</m> of a graph <m>G</m> that satisfies the following:
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> <m>G'</m> is connected; </li>
			<li> if <m>G''</m> is a subgraph of <m>G</m> such that <m>G''</m> is connected and <m>G' \preceq G''</m>, then <m>G'' = G'</m> </li>
		</ol>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<example><title>Breaking a nonconnected graph into connected components</title>
	<p>
	Considering <xref ref="figure-paths-components" /> below as a single graph,
	we have placed the connected components (of which there are three) into boxes.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-paths-components">
		<caption>A nonconnected graph as a collection of connected subgraphs.</caption>
		<image width="30%">
			<description>A graph to map the possible paths in another graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/components.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	This nonconnected graph has other connected subgraphs.
	For example, the subgraph that contains only the left-most two vertices joined by a single edge is a connected subgraph.
	But that connected graph is not a connected component because it is a subgraph of a larger connected subgraph.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Connected components do not depend on how the graph is represented diagrammatically</title>
	<figure xml:id="figure-paths-components-overlap-or-not">
		<caption>Two different representations of the same nonconnected graph.</caption>
		<sbsgroup>
			<sidebyside><figure>
				<caption>Overlapping connected components.</caption>
				<image>
					<description>A nonconnected graph drawn with overlapping connected components.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/components-overlap-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>
			<sidebyside><figure>
				<caption>Non-overlapping connected components.</caption>
				<image>
					<description>A nonconnected graph drawn with non-overlapping connected components.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/components-overlap-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>
		</sbsgroup>
	</figure>
	<p>
	The two graphs in <xref ref="figure-paths-components-overlap-or-not" /> are in fact the same graph,
	just with different diagrammatic representations.
	In the second version of the graph,
	we have again identified connected components by placing each of them in a box.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>A connected graph has one component</title>
	<p> If a graph is connected, then the entire graph is a largest connected subgraph possible. </p>
	<figure>
		<caption>A connected graph with one connected component.</caption>
		<image width="27%">
			<description>A connected graph with one connected component.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/components-connected-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

<note><p>
	As in our <xref ref="definition-paths-connected-component-working" text="custom">working definition</xref>,
	informally the <term>connected components</term> of a graph <m>G</m> are the <q>largest</q> subgraphs of <m>G</m> that are connected.
	The second condition in the
	<xref ref="definition-paths-connected-component-formal" text="custom">formal definition</xref>
	is just a positive way of stating the
	<xref ref="definition-paths-connected-component-working" text="custom">working definition</xref>.
	We will make the general notion of <q>largest</q> more precise in a similar way
	in <xref ref="chapter-partial-orders" />
	(see the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-partial-orders-maximal" text="title" /></term>,
	the <xref ref="test-partial-orders-maximal-minimal" text="custom">Test for Maximal/Minimal Elements</xref>,
	as well as <xref ref="example-partial-orders-connected-components-are-maximal" />).
</p></note>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-paths-min-edges-connected-graph">
	<title>A lower bound for the number of edges in a connected graph</title>
<!-- \label{THEOREM::min.edges.connected.graph} -->
	<statement><p> If <m>G = (V,E)</m> is connected and <m>\abs{V} = n</m>, then <m>\abs{E} \ge n - 1</m>. </p></statement>
	<proof>
		<p> By (strong) induction. </p>
		<case><title>Base case <m>n=1</m></title><p>
			Every graph with only one vertex is connected and satisfies <m>\abs{E} \ge 0</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Induction step</title>
		 	<p>
			Assume <m>k \ge 1</m> and the statement is true for all <m>n \le k</m>.
			Let <m>G = (V,E)</m> be a connected graph with <m>k + 1</m> vertices.
			We must show <m>\abs{E} \ge k</m>.
			</p><p>
			Arbitrarily choose some vertex <m>v_0 \in V</m>, and let <m>G' = (V', E')</m> be the graph obtained from <m>G</m> by removing <m>v_0</m> and all edges incident to it.
			Unfortunately, <m>G'</m> might not be connected.
			Let <m>G_1', \dotsc, G_\ell'</m> be its connected components.
			Write <m>G_i' = (V_i',E_i')</m>, and let <m>n_i = \abs{V_i'}</m>.
			Then each <m>G_i'</m> is connected and has at most <m>k</m> vertices, so the induction hypothesis applies.
			Also note that <m>n_1 + \dotsb + n_\ell = k</m>, since every vertex of <m>G</m> except <m>v_0</m> is part of exactly one subgraph <m>G_i'</m>.
			</p>
			<figure>
				<caption>Removing <q>extra</q> vertex <m>v_0</m>, splitting remaining subgraph into connected components.</caption>
				<sidebyside widths="26% 26%">
					<figure>
						<caption><q>Extra</q> vertex <m>v_0</m> and the remaining subgraph <m>G'</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>A depiction of removing one vertex from a graph.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/remove-v0.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
					<figure>
						<caption>Subgraph <m>G'</m> split into connected components.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>A depiction of removing one vertex from a graph and splitting remaining subgraph into connected components.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/remove-v0-components.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
				</sidebyside>
			</figure>
			<p>
			Therefore, using our induction hypothesis we may calculate
			<md>
				<mrow> \abs{E} \amp = \abs{E'} + \abs{\{\text{edges in } G \text{ incident to } v_0\}} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \abs{E_1'} + \dotsb \abs{E_\ell'} + \abs{\{\text{edges in } G \text{ incident to } v_0\}} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp \ge (n_1 - 1) + \dotsb + (n_\ell - 1) + \abs{\{\text{edges in } G \text{ incident to } v_0\}} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = k - \ell + \abs{\{\text{edges in } G \text{ incident to } v_0\}}. </mrow>
			</md>
			However, since <m>G</m> is connected, <m>v_0</m> must be the glue keeping the subgraphs <m>\{G_i'\}</m> together.
			That is, for each <m>i</m> there must be at least one edge between <m>v_0</m> and some vertex of <m>G_i'</m>.
			Therefore,
			<md>
				<mrow> \abs{E} \amp \ge k - \ell + \abs{\{\text{edges in } G \text{ incident to } v_0\}} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp \ge k - \ell + \ell </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = k. </mrow>
			</md>
			</p>
		</case>
	</proof>
</theorem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-paths-edge-connectivity">
<title>Articulation vertices, bridges, and edge connectivity</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>articulation vertex</title>
		<idx>articulation vertex</idx>
		<idx><h>vertex</h><h>articulation</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>vertex</h><h>articulation</h></idx>
		<p>
		a vertex of a graph such that, if it were to be removed (along with any edges incident to it),
		the resulting subgraph would have more connected components than the original
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>bridge</title>
		<idx>bridge</idx>
		<idx><h>edge</h><h>bridge</h></idx>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>edge</h><h>bridge</h></idx>
		<p>
		an edge of a graph such that, if it were to be removed,
		the resulting subgraph would have more connected components than the original
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>An articulation vertex</title>
	<p>
	In the graph of <xref ref="figure-paths-two-diamonds" />,
	the central vertex that is common to both diamond-shaped subgraphs is an articulation vertex,
	as removing it and all edges incident to it would leave two unconnected <q>ears</q> on the outside of the two diamond shapes.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-paths-two-diamonds">
		<caption>A graph featuring a single, central articulation vertex.</caption>
		<image width="30%">
			<description>A graph featuring a single, central articulation vertex.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/two-diamonds.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

<example>
	<title>A bridge between two articulation vertices</title>
	<p>
	In the graph of <xref ref="figure-paths-bridge-two-diamonds" />,
	edge <m>e</m> is a bridge,
	and each of <m>v</m> and <m>v'</m> are articulation vertices.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-paths-bridge-two-diamonds">
		<caption>A graph featuring a bridge between two articulation vertices.</caption>
		<image width="45%">
			<description>A graph featuring a bridge between two articulation vertices.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/bridge-two-diamonds.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

<remark><p>
	In the proof of <xref ref="theorem-paths-min-edges-connected-graph" />,
	our conception was that <q>extra</q> vertex <m>v_0</m> was an articulation vertex,
	where removing it would create a subgraph <m>G'</m> that would be split into connected components
	<m>G_1', \dotsc, G_\ell'</m>.
	(Though it is possible <m>v_0</m> is <em>not</em> an articulation vertex,
	if subgraph <m>G'</m> is connected.)
</p></remark>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>edge connectivity</title>
	<idx><h>edge</h><h>connectivity</h></idx>
	<idx><h>graph</h><h>edge</h><h>connectivity</h></idx>
	<p> the minimum number of edges that must be removed from a connected graph to obtain a nonconnected subgraph </p>
</li></dl></p>

<remark><p>
	Edge connectivity measures redundancy in the graph,
	as each edge that can be removed <em>without</em> breaking the graph into nonconnected subgraphs must be incident to a pair of vertices that remain connected via some other walk through the graph.
</p></remark>

<example><p> The edge connectivity of the graph in <xref ref="figure-paths-two-diamonds" /> is <m>2</m>. </p></example>

<example>
	<title>Edge connectivity in a graph with a bridge</title>
	<p>
	A bridge represents a <q>single point of failure,</q>
	and every graph that contains a bridge has edge connectivity <m>1</m>.
	For example, removing the single edge <m>e</m> in the graph of <xref ref="figure-paths-bridge-two-diamonds" />
	breaks the graph into two nonconnected subgraphs.
	</p>
</example>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-paths-edge-connectivity-upperbd">
	<title>Two upper bounds for edge connectivity</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>G = (V,E)</m> is a connected graph.
		Let <m>n = \abs{V}</m>, <m>e = \abs{E}</m>, and let <m>d</m> be the smallest degree of any of the vertices of <m>G</m>.
		Then the edge connectivity of <m>G</m> cannot be greater than either of the integers <m>d</m> or <m>\floor{2 e / n}</m>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof>
		<p>
		First, if <m>v</m> is a vertex of <m>G</m> with <m>\deg v = d</m>,
		then removing all of the edges incident to <m>v</m> will cause <m>v</m> to become isolated and <m>G</m> to become nonconnected.
		So the edge connectivity of <m>G</m> cannot be greater than <m>d</m>.
		</p><p>
		Next, recall that the sum of the degrees of the vertices of <m>G</m> is equal to <m>2e</m>
		(<xref ref="theorem-graphs-sum-of-degrees" />).
		Using this, we have
		<me> 2e = \deg v_1 + \deg v_2 + \dotsb + \deg v_n \ge d + d + \dotsb + d = nd </me>.
		So <m>d \le 2 e / n</m>.
		The number <m>2e/n</m> is rational, but may not be an integer.
		However, <m>d</m> is definitely an integer, so we must have <m>d \le \floor{2e/n}</m>.
		Since we have already concluded that the edge connectivity of <m>G</m> is no greater than <m>d</m>,
		it also can be no greater than <m>\floor{2 e / n}</m>.
	</p></proof>
</proposition>

<remark><p>
	With <m>n</m> and <m>e</m> as in the statement of the theorem,
	<m>2 e</m> is equal to the sum of the degrees of the vertices
	(<xref ref="theorem-graphs-sum-of-degrees" />),
	so <m>2 e / n</m> is equal to the <em>average</em> degree of vertices in the graph.
</p></remark>

<problem xml:id="wexample-paths-treefort-commnet"> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement>
		<p>
		Your tree fort rivals have set up a communication system of tin cans and strings.
		You have mapped out their network as in <xref ref="figure-paths-comm-network" />.
		To minimize the risk of crab apple welts, what is the minimum number of strings you must cut to disrupt their communications?
		</p>
		<figure xml:id="figure-paths-comm-network">
			<caption>TreeFort CommNet.</caption>
			<image width="45%">
				<description>A communication network.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="paths.d/treefort-commnet.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</statement>
	<solution><p>
		There are <m>6</m> nodes and <m>10</m> edges,
		so <xref ref="proposition-paths-edge-connectivity-upperbd" /> tells that the edge connectivity must be no greater than <m>\floor{20/6} = 3</m>.
		By inspection, the edge connectivity is not <m>1</m> as there are no bridges.
		However, we may isolate either fort ALPHA or ECHO with two snips.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</section>

